==English==
===Etymology===
First used by Israeli troops during military raids in Palestine to provide especially favorable views of theatrical tactics and operations.  Later adopted by the U.S. in Iraq to avoid uncontrolled and independent coverage of Vietnam that made assault unpopular.

===Adjective===
# To be in a controlled reporting or public relations position with Israeli, or U.S., forces during a military engagement, and be escorted to places of unique advantage for the purpose of news or propaganda. 
# To be part of, and firmly, or securely surrounded.
# To be partially buried in concrete or planted in earth.
# To be snugly in bed with, or an integral part of.